Polls show Whitmer’s lead has stabilized in the last two weeks. RealClearPolitics average has her at 49.9%. I’d estimate she comes in right around 51% when all is said and done.

The election is soon enough to move this to a lock. With abortion rights on the ballot and going against an incumbent in a purple state who has consistently led in the polls, Tudor Dixon has no realistic path to victory here.
Polls have narrowed quite a lot on this one

In Michigan, a combination of factors sees us move this race back from Likely Democratic to Leans Democratic. [...]. Polling has also narrowed in this race, and Gretchen Whitmer now leads by mid-to-low single-digits. This is still a clear lead for Whitmer, but it’s clear that the race has tightened from Whitmer’s early September highs. The possibility Dixon pulls an upset is better than it seemed when we first moved this race to the Likely Democratic category. - Elections Daily, Oct 24, https://elections-daily.com/2022/10/24/republicans-gain-ground-in-house-races-michigan-while-democrats-see-high-hopes-in-kansas/

Not much polling, but the little we've got aren't even close. With the Michigan Right to Reproductive Freedom Initiative likely to be on the ballot this November (which will boost turnout for Democratic-leaning voters), the clear favorite is Governor Whitmer. Still, there's a lot of time left and a lot could change.

Finally looking at the 538 forecast: https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2022-election-forecast/governor/michigan/I do think Whitmer has a really good chance, given that she's the incumbent, her approval ratings are good, and the Republican candidates have had trouble getting on the ballot. But I'll leave a little more room than what the 538 forecast says for the R candidate to win, because unexpected things can happen.

I'm reminded of the time when Hillary was polling 20 points above Bernie in Michigan and he still won. We have a grand total of one poll of this race since May, from a 538 C/D rated pollster, 6 months out, with GOP candidates who still have extremely low name recognition.

Whitmore (sp?) has a strong record but in 2022, cannot count out Republicans in purple states

1) Seems like the disqualification of the GOP contenders was on a party line vote of the elections commission, deadlocked 2-2. Indicates to me they have a nonzero chance of success in court. Craig's lawsuit is in the Michigan court of claims, although I can't find the text of the suit (may not be public). Court of claims is also split 2-2 GOP/Dem appointees, so it's kind of 50-50 which judge gets this case, unless they do it en banc. Michigan supreme court appears to have a 4-3 Democratic majority at the moment so it's hard to see the case succeeding there. Possible there would be a federal challenge also, and the federal 6th circuit is GOP dominated, but I can't find any news reports of a federal suit, so I'm guessing that would have to follow a failure at state court, and probably not at all.
Reducing slightly until I can dig into the current situation

Thinking about it some more, the disqualification of the main Republican hopefuls from primary ballots could well split the Republican vote and hand an easy victory to Whitmer. The Republican vote could end up split between an official party candidate that few are excited about and one or even two major write-in candidates. I can't see how a write-in candidate could realistically win, because it would be hard to get all the voters they need to remember and accurately write a specific name, and some voters will just vote straight ticket, which is offered in Michigan (i.e., voting for all the members of one party on a ballot by marking only one box on the ballot). There will be legal challenges, but I just can't see those working, either. What do they want the courts to say - "oh, we're so sorry the people you hired forged signatures! That wasn't fair. Sure, you can be on the ballot, and we'll just waive the rules for you"? So, I’m increasing my forecast for a Democratic victory for now, but I’m also leaving room for the situation to change.

Plot twist: 5 out of 10 Republican candidates for governor are not going to be allowed on the ballot because they did not get the required number of signatures -- because too many of the signatures collected by firms they hired were found to be fraudulent. Craig and Johnson were 2 of the most important Republican candidates, and they are both now probably off the ballot entirely. At least Craig and Johnson have said they will mount legal challenges, but I don't see how they can win, unless election law is thrown away. 19 candidates for various positions didn't submit the minimum required number of signatures, so they're off the ballot. So I'm increasing my forecast for Whitmer.

She is beloved by a good portion of the state, even has a nickname , Big Gretch, and a rap song dedicated to her. Recent polls show a strong approval rating from Independents.

Whitmer has a good margin in the polls right now, but that is largely name ID. This will be a tight race with the historical trends favoring Republicans, but a lot is still developing in this race, and it is difficult to defeat an incumbent, regardless of the historical trends or the direction of the wave. If John James gets into the race and was the nominee, considering how close he performed against two incumbent Senators in 2018 and 2020 and his national fundraising base, I would move this to about 80% in favor of the Republicans.
Off-year election will help R candidate but incumbency will help Whitmer. Additionally, since term limits have been imposed both previous governors have served two consecutive terms.

"Republicans are feeling momentum after Virginia Gov.-elect Glenn Youngkin's victory in November, when he became the first Republican to win a statewide race in the blue-leaning state since 2009. The party says the political environment is prime for Republicans to oust a number of vulnerable Democratic governors this year, including Gov. Laura Kelly in Kansas and Gov. Gretchen Whitmer in Michigan." "The Cook Political Report shifted the race’s rating from “lean Democratic” to “toss-up” earlier this month. Cook also shifted the state’s Senate rating from “lean Democratic” to “toss-up.” Cook cited Biden’s declining approval ratings and the current state of the economy, including rising inflation, as the reasons for the changes." https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/587202-seven-most-vulnerable-governors-facing-reelection-in-2022
This one could go either way.

538 has it as lean D, and Biden won the state by 2.8% [1]. But I've been putting a bit more weight on Trafalgar polls recently, and they have the R challenger up 6 in a poll from September. Too early to put much weight on that, but I am putting some weight on it. Also since Whitmer is the incumbent that will help her a bit. This one feels kind of like a tossup, and I give the slight advantage to R for now.

Current governor has produced a very large number of voters who are dedicated to seeing her lose. She has not excited the democrats base. It may be close but those who will be sure to get out and vote are decidedly not in her camp.
I think the swing to the right will be strong and widespread.

Simple… a very large portion of 74 million Trump voters believe he lost due to election fraud. This was because MI’s democrat governor somehow “assisted” in that fraud. So now they see this as a chance to rectify the error for the next presidential election.
Incumbent Democratic governor Gretchen Whitmer is running for re-election to a second term. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_Michigan_gubernatorial_election
The Rs have a good candidate in James Craig but recent statewide elections have favored Ds.
Since 1994, the Michigan Governorship has entered a perfect 2 term cycle alternating between Democrat (D) and Republican (R) - 1994-2002 = R = 2 Term 2002-2010 = D = 2 Term 2010-2018 = R = 2 Term

I think it's been hard to be a governor over the past couple years, and Gov. Whitmer has certainly had her share of critics. As of a few months ago, she was holding her own in approval ratings: https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2021/09/20/gretchen-whitmer-job-approval-falls-splitting-michigan-voters-poll-finds/8383210002/ But the polls of a few months ago point towards a Republican win. Let's see how things go over the coming months, though, as the Omicron wave comes and goes, the weather is nicer, supply chains ease, GM Bolt vehicle production resumes, and construction and renovations proceed to set up an EV battery plant and get other plants ready for EV production. https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/gm-extend-production-halt-ev-chevrolet-bolt-through-february-2021-12-20/ https://detroit.cbslocal.com/2021/12/10/gm-venture-picks-michigan-for-3rd-us-based-electric-vehicle-battery-plant/

Would be a solid R due to the national environment but incumbent with above water approval rating makes it a closer race than it would otherwise be
Polling is currently close, but it is a very long time since an incumbent failed to win reelection in the state.

Dems have the edge in party registration, but I suspect the GOP will have the edge in turnout. As Nate Cohn said in the NYT (re Biden), the Pres (or Gov) is credited/blamed for the current state of affairs, whether they deserve it or not. Michigan's been hit extremely hard by Delta and will probably be hit even harder by Omicron, mostly because too few people are willing to vax and mask. Governor Whitmer is being blamed for the outcome. It's still early, so I still have hope things will turn around, but this is my best assessment for the moment.

I had to go back to 1961 before the incumbent had lost in their second election, thus I think there is a strong likelihood Whitmer wins in 2022. However, 2022 is expected to be a strong year for Republicans and therefore, giving them some benefit because of the enthusiasm, seems right to me.
The potential match up plus folks outside the city are looking forward to a rematch.

Incumbent governor is +2 net approval going into the election year, and it's a true battleground state -- although it should be a wave year for the opposition party. Overall this seems more like 50/50 to me than the crowd's 80/20
